    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey!  \nYes, normalizing your features is crucial because it lets the learning algorithm converge faster and more reliably.  \nWhen one feature ranges from 0–1 and another from 1000–5000, the gradient‑based optimizer (like SGD or Adam) will see very different “slopes” for each feature, which can lead to uneven update steps.  \nThink of it like a goblin‑led race: if one runner starts at 0 and the other at 1000, the one at 0 will finish much sooner unless you rescale the distances so both start at roughly the same point.  \n\n**Why it matters**\n\n1. **Gradient magnitude** – The optimizer’s step size is proportional to the magnitude of the gradients.  \n   * If a feature has a huge range, its gradient can be much larger than that of a small‑range feature.  \n   * Normalizing brings the features to a similar scale, so each gradient contributes roughly the same “push” to the weights.\n\n2. **Convergence speed** – With scaled features, the loss surface becomes smoother and the optimizer can take larger, more consistent steps.  \n   * You’ll typically see fewer",
